The '''black-legged seriema''' ('''''Chunga burmeisteri''''') is one of two living [[species]] of seriemas in the family [[Cariamidae]]. It is found from southeastern  [[Bolivia]] and northern [[Paraguay]] south into north-central [[Argentina]]. It is a large, mostly grey bird with a long neck, a long tail, and long, slender black legs. Its belly, vent and thighs are yellowish-white. The sexes look similar, as do immature birds, though the latter are more patterned on head, neck and back. First described for science by [[Gustav Hartlaub]] in 1860, it is [[monotypic]], with no subspecies. Like its [[red-legged seriema|red-legged cousin]], it is an [[omnivore]]. It seldom flies, instead pursuing prey and eluding danger on foot. Its loud calls, said to sound like [[kookaburra]]s, [[turkey (bird)|turkeys]] or yelping dogs, are often given in duet. Little is known about its breeding ecology. It is known to breed in November and December, building a platform nest of sticks and laying two white eggs, which are sometimes marked with a few brownish or purple spots. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] rates the species as one of [[least concern]], due to its large range and apparently stable numbers.

==Taxonomy==
German ornithologist [[Gustav Hartlaub]] first [[scientific description|described]] the black-legged seriema for science in 1860,{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}} using information passed to him by [[Hermann Burmeister]], another German zoologist who was living and working in South America at the time. Hartlaub named it ''Dicholophus burmeisteri''.{{sfn|Hartlaub|1860|p=334}} Both Hartlaub and Burmeister suggested that ''Chunga'' be established as a subgenus of ''Dicholophus'', the genus which already contained the [[red-legged seriema]], based on small differences between the species.{{sfn|Hartlaub|1860|p=335}} However, it was quickly elevated to the status of a full [[genus]]. The black-legged seriema, which has no [[subspecies]], is the only extant species in the genus.{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}} The other member of the genus, ''[[Chunga incerta]]'', lived in the mid to late [[Pliocene]].{{sfn|Tambussi|Ubilla|Acosta Hospitaleche|Perea|2005|p=265}} The black-legged seriema and its close relative the red-legged seriema are the only two living members of the small family [[Cariamidae]].{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}}

The genus name ''Chunga'' comes directly from the name given to the black-legged seriema by Spanish residents of Argentina.{{sfn|Hartlaub|1860|p=335}} The species name ''burmeisteri'' honors Hermann Burmeister, who had provided Hartlaub with information about the bird.{{sfn|Hartlaub|1860|p=335}} "Seriema" is a [[Latin]]ized word, invented in the mid-19th century and taken directly from the [[Tupi language|Tupi]] word ''siriema'', which means "crested".{{sfn|Lexico|2021|ref=Lexico}}

==Description==
The black-legged seriema is a large bird, measuring some {{convert|70|–|85|cm|abbr=on}} in length, and weighing roughly {{convert|1.2|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=234}} This makes it one of the largest ground-dwelling birds in the [[Neotropics]]; only the red-legged seriema and the [[Rhea (bird)|rhea]]s are larger.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=234}} It is long-necked and long-tailed, with very long, slender legs and short, rounded wings.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|pp=234–235}}{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}} Overall, it is ash-grey in colour, though closer examination shows that the "grey" body feathers are actually finely [[wikt:vermiculated|vermiculated]] with black and white.{{sfn|Hartlaub|1860|p=335}} It has an inconspicuous frontal crest, composed of erect, hairlike bristles.{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=529}} It has whitish {{birdgloss|supercilia}} and {{birdgloss|lores}}, and the feathers on its crown and nape are barred in black and white.{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=530}} Its belly is paler grey, and its lower abdomen, {{birdgloss|crissum}} and thighs are yellowish-white.{{sfn|Hartlaub|1860|p=335}} The [[flight feather]]s on the wings are thickly barred with black and white,{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}} and its grey tail is barred and narrowly tipped with black.{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=530}} Its feathers are loosely webbed, giving the bird a "soft" appearance.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=234}} Those on its nape are particularly long, forming an inconspicuous crest. Its stout black [[beak|bill]] has a strongly [[wikt:decurved|decurved]] {{birdgloss|culmen}} and a small hook at the tip.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=235}} Its [[iris (eye)|iris]] is reddish-brown, and its legs are dark-grey to black.{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}}{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=530}} Its feet have three short front toes with very sharp claws, and one small elevated hind toe which also found on [[Dromaeosauridae]].{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=235}} The sexes look alike, and youngsters are similar, though somewhat more patterned.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=234}} The latters' heads, necks and breasts are barred, and their backs and {{birdgloss|upperwing coverts}} are speckled with white.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=239}}

===Vocalisations===
Its call notes are a series of yelps and barks, said to sound like a [[wild turkey|turkey]], a [[kookaburra]] or a small dog.{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}}{{sfn|Boyle|1917|p=295}} Pairs call in tandem, with the duet said to be loud, slow and evenly-pitched, but somewhat harsh and unmusical.{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}}

===Similar species===
The only species that the black-legged seriema could conceivably be confused with is the red-legged seriema. Though similar in general appearance, the black-legged seriema is smaller, and lacks the distinctive frontal crest of its red-legged cousin. It has a black bill and dark legs, rather than a red bill and red legs,{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}} and a dark eye rather than a pale one.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=239}} Although the two overlap locally in their ranges,{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}} they tend to live in different habitats.{{sfn|Brooks|2014|p=235}}

==Distribution and habitat==
Found from southeastern Bolivia and northern Paraguay south into north-central Argentina, the black-legged seriema is a dry-country bird of [[savanna]], [[shrubland]] and [[dry forest|dry, open forest]], including the [[Gran Chaco|Dry Chaco]] and the [[Monte Desert]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}}{{sfn|Pearman|Areta|2020|p=40}}{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=530}} Perhaps surprisingly, the species was not known from Bolivia until the late 1970s.{{sfn|Schmitt|Cole|1981|p=182}} It is generally found at elevations below {{convert|800|m|abbr=on}},{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}} lower than the elevations at which the red-legged seriema is typically found.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=239}} Though it will forage in untreed areas, including cultivated fields and grassy plains, it only does so when there are wooded areas nearby.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=235}}

==Behaviour==
The black-legged seriema spends much of its time on the ground, and flies only reluctantly. It is a fast runner, and typically chases prey and eludes predators on foot. If pressed, it is capable of short flight – rapid flapping, followed by a glide.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=235}} It sometimes flies up into trees, though it will preferentially jump to lower branches. Although it is primarily a sedentary species, some local movements may occur. In Paraguay, for example, it is known to move out of some areas of the chaco in response to cooler weather.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=235}}

===Food and feeding===
Black-legged seriemas are [[omnivorous]]. Insects, particularly [[beetle]]s and [[locust]]s, make up a significant portion of their diet, and they take the occasional rodent.{{sfn|Boyle|1917|p=295}} They also eat plant material, including leaves, grass and seeds.{{sfn|Boyle|1917|p=295}} They often hunt around the feet of livestock, which presumably flush insects as they move.{{sfn|Boyle|1917|p=295}}

===Breeding===
The breeding behaviour of the black-legged seriema is not well-known. It is thought to breed primarily from November into December. It [[bird nest|nests]] solitarily, with both members of the pair building a platform of sticks in a tree. The female lays two white eggs, which measure {{convert|56|–|61|mm|abbr=on}} x {{convert|42|–|46|mm|abbr=on}} and may have a few brown or pale purple spots.{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=237}}

==Relationship with humans==
[[Indigenous peoples]] within the black-legged seriema's range hunt seriemas and collect their eggs for food.{{sfn|Boyle|1917|p=296}} This has occurred from prehistoric times through as recently as 2003.{{sfn|del Papa|2016|p=78}}{{sfn|Altrichter|2006|p=2723}} The [[Toba people]] of Argentina make a [[poultice]] of the bird's manure to treat boils and abscesses.{{sfn|Martínez|Barboza|2010|p=96}}

==Conservation status==
Because of the black-legged seriema's very large range and apparently stable population, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] considers it be a species of [[least concern]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}} Although its numbers have not been quantified, it is said to be "fairly common" throughout its range in Argentina. Its status in Bolivia and Paraguay is not well-documented.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}}{{sfn|Gonzaga|1996|p=238}} It is potentially impacted by habitat loss and fragmentation. One study in Argentina found the bird disappeared from parts of its former range once the forest had been fragmented into plots of less than {{convert|280|ha|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Dardanelli|Nores|Nores|2006|p=691}}

It is known to harbour the [[chewing louse]] species ''[[Tinamotaecola wardi]]'', ''[[Tinamotaecola andinae]]'', ''[[Colpocephalum cristatae]]'' and ''[[Colpocephalum caudatum]]''.{{sfn|Cicchino|Valim|González-Acuña|2014|pp=351, 359}}{{sfn|Catanach|Valim|Weckstein|Johnson|2018}}{{sfn|Thompson|1938|p=268}}

